                        <accMat>
                            <p xml:id="accMat1">An envelope glued to the inside of the front cover, containing a letter from 
                                <persName ref="PRS15333Fasulo"><roleName type="rank">col.</roleName> Giuseppe Fasulo</persName> to
                                    <q xml:lang="it"><persName ref="PRS7170Moreno"><roleName type="rank">Comm.</roleName>
                                    <roleName type="title">Dott.</roleName> Moreno</persName>, Segretario Generale, Governo di Galla e
                                    Sidamo, Gimma</q>. The letter, dated <placeName ref="LOC4964Naqamt">Lekemti</placeName>, 
                                    <date when="1937-09-25">25th September 1937</date>, is written on a sheet of paper measuring 310 x 210 mm.
                                    It contains a translation of the two texts by <persName ref="PRS3182ContiRo"/> entitled <title>TRADUZIONE 
                                    DEL MANOSCRITTO DELLA STORIA DEI GALLI REDATTO A CURA DEI DE GIAC GABRESGHIER ED
                                    APTEMARIAM</title>, and is indicated as ‘Texte A’ in <bibl><ptr target="bm:Strelcyn1976Catalogue"/>
                                    <citedRange unit="page">145</citedRange></bibl>. The letter is typewritten, and there is a handwritten postscript.
                                    The typewritten text spans 40 lines on the front side and appears to be a condensed version of the Amharic texts. 
                                    It is probably the summarising character that prompted Carlo to begin a proper translation of the Amharic texts 
                                    <persName ref="PRS3182ContiRo"/> to begin a proper translation of the Amharic texts (<ref target="#accMat2"/>).
                                <q xml:lang="it">Il paese dei <choice resp="PRS8999Strelcyn"><sic>Borama</sic>
                                    <corr><persName ref="PRS2845Booran">Borana</persName></corr></choice> Horro Ualabù. — Maccià e 
                                    Tulamà erano due fratelli figli di Borana. Erano dei pastori che vivevano nomadi e si nutrivano di carne, di latte e di 
                                    caccia. — Un giorno, girando per i paesi, videro, trascinato dalla corrente, un piccolo cesto contenente engera, carne ed 
                                    un coltello. — <gap reason="ellipsis"/></q></p>
                            <p xml:id="accMat2">Three sheets of unbound paper of ca. 310 x 220 mm with a translation by 
                                <persName ref="PRS3182ContiRo"/> of the Amharic texts (<ref target="ms_i1.2"/> and <ref target="ms_i1.1"/>), 
                                of which only the first few pages up to <locus target="#5r"/> were completed. Indicated in as ‘Texte B’ in
                                <bibl><ptr target="bm:Strelcyn1976Catalogue"/><citedRange unit="page">145</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
                        </accMat>
